Waitemata Harbour, from Waterview to Hobsonville on the south-west side of the central harbour. They form a flat, relatively hard substrate in the middle and high tidal areas in a number of places, particularly around Pollen Island and the ends of Te Atatu and Hobsonville Peninsulas.

Waitemata Harbour. A sublittoral fringe of large brown seaweeds grows along the low tide line around the edge of the outer half of the central Waitemata Harbour. This fringe is denser and contains more species on the very edge of the main harbour channel (e.g., end of Meola Reef, Stanley Pt, Northcote Pt) and nearer the harbour entrance (e.g., Devonport, Waterfront Drive). The sublittoral fringe extends up the harbour as far as Soldiers Bay on the north shore and as far as the north tip of Te Atatu Peninsula on the southern shore. The largest area of sublittoral fringe in the central Waitemata Harbour is exposed at spring low tide in the entrance channel to Hobson Bay, adjacent to the intersection of Waterfront Drive and Ngapipi Road.
Waitemata Harbour. At high tide level near the end of Te Atatu Peninsula
Waitemata Harbour. Beside the boat ramp at Orakei Basin

Waitemata Harbour. Hard reefs and low cliffs in places inside Orakei Basin, especially near the boat ramp and the ski club, and also on either side of Purewa Creek both above and just below the Orakei Road bridge. Tuff also forms all the intertidal reefs and cliffs around North Head. Tuff forms low reefs, surrounded by mud, alongside the Northern Motorway on the west side of Shoal Bay.

Waitemata Harbour. Intertidal cliffs and reefs of Waitemata sandstone occur along most of the northern side of the central harbour, from Stanley Point to Greenhithe. They are particularly pronounced around the seaward ends of points that stick out into the harbour (e.g., Stanley, Northcote, Birkenhead and Kauri Points). Coastal sandstone cliffs and reefs are still present around parts of Hobson Bay, from the harbour bridge to Pt Chevalier and around the end of Hobsonville Peninsula. Several intertidal sandstone reefs are present seaward of the Waterfront Drive and in the middle of the harbour off Kauri Point (e.g., Boat Rock) and Herne Bay (Watchman Island).

Waitemata Harbour. Mangrove forest grows extensively in the upper part of the intertidal zone around the sheltered fringes of the central Waitemata Harbour. Mangroves form the most extensive forest areas on the banks of the elongate Whau and Henderson estuaries and in the upper reaches of the many tidal embayments - particularly Ngataringa Bay, Shoal Bay and Hellyers Creek on the North Shore, and Hobson Bay and Pollen Island Marine Reserve on the south shore. A large area of mangrove forest also grows off the north end of Te Atatu Peninsula.

Waitemata Harbour. Natural basalt reefs are only present in the central Waitemata Harbour in three places. A small area of high tide basalt reef (toe of lava flow from Little Rangitoto volcano) occurs among low mangroves beside Shore Road on the edge of Hobson Bay, between St Kentigerns Primary School and the plant nursery. A 500 m strip of dark basalt reefs and low cliffs (Mt Victoria lava flow), extending from high tide to shallow subtidal level, runs along the Devonport foreshore from Torpedo Bay almost to Devonport Wharf. The largest natural basalt reef is Meola Reef which extends ca. 1 km out into Waitemata Harbour from the mouth of Meola and Motion Creeks

Waitemata Harbour. On Pollen Island and in the adjacent area across the NW Motorway on the east side of the Whau River (outside the Marine Reserve). Remnants of a once more extensive area occur on the landward side of Shore Rd, adjacent to Portland Rd on the edge of Hobson Bay, Remuera. Small patches or fringing ribbons of rush salt marsh also occur adjacent to mangrove forest up the Whau River, Henderson Creek and in Shoal Bay.
